48:58.501 --> 49:00.545
DEALER: You don't know?

49:00.545 --> 49:01.796
‐ Wise guy.

49:04.424 --> 49:06.926
‐ What the fuck is this?

49:06.926 --> 49:08.887
‐ So you got anything
on a prescription drug

49:08.887 --> 49:10.680
called OxyContin?

49:10.680 --> 49:13.766
Have there been any spikes
in crime related to it?

49:13.766 --> 49:15.435
Yeah, I'll hold.

49:15.435 --> 49:17.270
Foster care‐‐

49:17.270 --> 49:19.898
the foster care occupancy
has tripled?

49:19.898 --> 49:23.359
Increase in child abandonment.

49:23.359 --> 49:26.112
How long have you seen
this trend?

49:26.112 --> 49:28.823
Local jails overflowing.

49:28.823 --> 49:32.160
Increase in prostitution.

49:32.160 --> 49:34.829
Yes, um, do you got anything
on a prescription drug

49:34.829 --> 49:36.414
called OxyContin?

49:36.414 --> 49:38.208
Uh, your lawn mower was stolen?

49:38.208 --> 49:40.960
No, I‐I can't help you
with that.

49:40.960 --> 49:43.338
So they just broke
into the pharmacy

49:43.338 --> 49:45.381
and only took OxyContin?

49:45.381 --> 49:47.634
Nothing else?

49:47.634 --> 49:50.803
♪ ♪

49:50.803 --> 49:53.306
This is Bridget Meyer
with the DEA.

49:53.306 --> 49:57.101
Um, I know it's late,
but I wanted to confirm

49:57.101 --> 50:00.271
some intel I got
about your pharmacy.

50:00.271 --> 50:01.981
I know this is
Diversion's domain.

50:01.981 --> 50:03.274
‐ That's correct.

50:03.274 --> 50:05.652
‐ But in a raid
on a mid‐level cocaine bust,

50:05.652 --> 50:08.071
we uncovered a bag
filled with OxyContin tablets

50:08.071 --> 50:11.241
for distribution,
so I did a little digging.

50:11.241 --> 50:14.369
This drug has only been
on the market for three years,

50:14.369 --> 50:17.372
and there's already been
a spike in overdoses

50:17.372 --> 50:20.875
and crime rates in rural parts
of Kentucky, Maine,

50:20.875 --> 50:23.211
Ohio, Pennsylvania,
and Virginia,

50:23.211 --> 50:26.381
all areas where this drug
was first launched.

50:26.381 --> 50:28.925
‐ Jermaine,
where's Diversion on this?

50:28.925 --> 50:30.552
‐ Opioid use has been
totally redefined

50:30.552 --> 50:31.928
in the last few years.

50:31.928 --> 50:34.430
They're completed accepted
in the medical community.

50:34.430 --> 50:37.308
The prevailing sentiment
is that not prescribing opioids

50:37.308 --> 50:39.102
is considered inhumane.

50:39.102 --> 50:42.230
‐ So Diversion isn't concerned
with illegal opioid sales?

50:42.230 --> 50:44.190
‐ With all due respect, sir,
the diversion division

50:44.190 --> 50:45.984
is the most underfunded
and understaffed unit

50:45.984 --> 50:47.610
in this building.
‐ Excuse me?

50:47.610 --> 50:49.112
‐ I'm just stating a fact.

50:49.112 --> 50:50.697
We're also the most demoralized

50:50.697 --> 50:53.074
since you make it pretty clear
the DEA's priorities

50:53.074 --> 50:54.993
are not illegal use
of prescription drugs.

50:54.993 --> 50:57.203
‐ And how many Diversion agents
get killed

50:57.203 --> 50:58.663
on the job every year?

50:58.663 --> 51:00.290
Zero.

51:00.290 --> 51:02.375
I got Operation agents
like Bridget here

51:02.375 --> 51:03.876
dying on the front lines.

51:03.876 --> 51:06.629
And she's doing it in high
heels and a quinceañera dress.

51:06.629 --> 51:09.591
So excuse me if I don't have
time to give you a pep talk

51:09.591 --> 51:11.551
about stopping
Joey Sticky Fingers

51:11.551 --> 51:13.344
from stealing Daddy's Vicodin.

51:13.344 --> 51:15.597
‐ Sir, I understand
stopping Joey Sticky Fingers

51:15.597 --> 51:17.015
isn't a priority,

51:17.015 --> 51:20.143
but there might be a unique
situation brewing here.

51:20.143 --> 51:21.978
I thought we could start
with the FDA

51:21.978 --> 51:23.521
and try to tighten up
sales of this drug‐‐

51:23.521 --> 51:26.399
‐ The FDA granted OxyContin
a unique label

51:26.399 --> 51:28.443
saying it was less addictive
than other opioids,

51:28.443 --> 51:31.154
so they're not gonna be
interested or helpful.

51:31.154 --> 51:32.947
Curbing opioid use goes against

51:32.947 --> 51:35.408
the entire national narrative
on the subject.

51:35.408 --> 51:41.998
♪ ♪

51:42.999 --> 51:45.627
‐ So I heard
there's a new guy.

51:45.627 --> 51:47.211
Is he down
with you carrying a gun

51:47.211 --> 51:48.755
and storming into buildings?

51:48.755 --> 51:51.466
‐ Uh, yeah. He kind of digs it.

51:51.466 --> 51:53.968
KAREN: Hmm, well, that's
a needle in a haystack.

51:53.968 --> 51:55.511
But I guess
those days are done,

51:55.511 --> 51:57.555
since you transferred
to Diversion.

51:57.555 --> 51:59.515
‐ I didn't transfer.

51:59.515 --> 52:02.185
I'm just interested
in OxyContin.

52:02.185 --> 52:03.811
I understand
it was given a label

52:03.811 --> 52:06.481
saying it was less addictive
than other opioids.

52:07.982 --> 52:09.484
Is that unusual?

52:09.484 --> 52:10.735
‐ It was a first.

52:10.735 --> 52:12.737
BRIDGET: How'd that come about?

52:12.737 --> 52:15.448
‐ The wording of the label
or the approval of it?

52:15.448 --> 52:18.618
‐ The approval.
Was it standard?

52:20.495 --> 52:22.497
‐ Curtis got some pushback.

52:22.497 --> 52:23.998
BRIDGET: Curtis?

52:23.998 --> 52:26.250
‐ Curtis Wright, he's
the medical review officer.

52:26.250 --> 52:28.628
He approved the label.

52:28.628 --> 52:30.838
‐ What was the pushback?

52:30.838 --> 52:32.715
‐ That there wasn't a need
to give it a label

52:32.715 --> 52:35.968
differentiating it
from other Class II narcotics.

52:35.968 --> 52:39.180
‐ And why was it given?
‐ I don't know the details.

52:39.180 --> 52:42.308
I just know
that there was pushback.

52:42.308 --> 52:43.559
‐ Is there something
I should know

52:43.559 --> 52:45.311
about the approval process?

52:47.772 --> 52:50.066
‐ Was there any kind
of internal debate

52:50.066 --> 52:51.859
over the wording of the label?

52:53.695 --> 52:55.363
‐ I would call it
a disagreement.

52:55.363 --> 52:56.656
Some people didn't think

52:56.656 --> 52:58.991
that Purdue had proven
their claims were true.

52:58.991 --> 53:00.576
‐ Hmm, did they have
any studies

53:00.576 --> 53:02.412
that showed
it was less addictive?

53:02.412 --> 53:05.415
‐ Those studies
weren't conducted.

53:05.415 --> 53:08.292
‐ [scoffs]
And why not?

53:08.292 --> 53:10.795
‐ Purdue agreed
to a Class II classification,

53:10.795 --> 53:13.881
which meant that they agreed
that it could be abused,

53:13.881 --> 53:17.427
so they argued that
there was no need to test

53:17.427 --> 53:19.095
for what they were
already agreeing to.

53:19.095 --> 53:21.472
‐ So let me
get this straight.

53:21.472 --> 53:24.350
The FDA approves
this unprecedented label

53:24.350 --> 53:27.270
because Purdue claims
it's less prone to abuse.

53:27.270 --> 53:29.439
KAREN: Correct.
They are argued that

53:29.439 --> 53:31.399
because
of the time‐release system,

53:31.399 --> 53:33.359
they should be given
a unique classification.

53:33.359 --> 53:35.319
‐ Curtis Wright just
take their word for it?

53:35.319 --> 53:38.030
‐ Ms. Moles cannot comment
on Mr. Wright's state of mind.

53:40.116 --> 53:41.617
‐ Have you spoken to Curtis?

53:41.617 --> 53:44.120
‐ We wanted
to get background first.

53:44.120 --> 53:46.330
Is he still the review officer?

53:48.332 --> 53:50.084
‐ You don't know.

53:51.753 --> 53:53.504
RICK: And then, uh,
less than two years later,

53:53.504 --> 53:55.631
after the drug hits the market,

53:55.631 --> 53:57.383
Curtis Wright resigns
from the FDA.

53:57.383 --> 53:59.218
‐ You want to take a guess
where he lands?

53:59.218 --> 54:00.636
‐ You're kidding me.

54:00.636 --> 54:02.346
‐ He ends up at Purdue Pharma

54:02.346 --> 54:05.516
as executive director
of medical affairs.

54:05.516 --> 54:07.727
‐ So the FDA grants
an unusual label

54:07.727 --> 54:09.187
that turns out not to be true,

54:09.187 --> 54:12.231
and the guy who approved it
goes to work for the company

54:12.231 --> 54:14.233
that made billions
off the label?

54:14.233 --> 54:17.820
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ That is correct, sir.

54:17.820 --> 54:19.363
‐ We'd like to open
an investigation

54:19.363 --> 54:20.698
into Curtis Wright.

54:23.201 --> 54:24.786
‐ Yeah, I think you should.

54:27.830 --> 54:30.291
‐ Well, he seems engaged.
‐ For now.

54:30.291 --> 54:32.293
See what happens when
Main Justice hears about it.

54:32.293 --> 54:34.170
‐ You think
that DEA agent was right?

54:34.170 --> 54:36.339
We're gonna get shut down
by the higher‐ups?

54:36.339 --> 54:37.840
‐ Wouldn't surprise me.

54:37.840 --> 54:39.383
‐ I'll meet you downstairs.

54:42.929 --> 54:45.932
[retching]

54:45.932 --> 54:52.939
♪ ♪

54:57.985 --> 55:00.988
‐ [screaming in pain]

55:02.949 --> 55:05.952
[telephone rings]

55:08.579 --> 55:11.582
‐ Hello.

55:11.582 --> 55:13.209
Yeah.

55:13.209 --> 55:15.878
Bets, I'm gonna lift that shirt
up for you now, all right?

55:15.878 --> 55:17.255
‐ All right.
SAMUEL: All right.

55:17.255 --> 55:18.756
BETSY: Kind of hurts to move,
though.

55:18.756 --> 55:20.758
‐ All right.
I'll be careful.

55:20.758 --> 55:22.969
BETSY: [groaning]

55:22.969 --> 55:24.345
‐ Okay?
BETSY: Mm‐hmm.

55:28.266 --> 55:29.600
‐ Oh!

55:29.600 --> 55:31.227
BETSY: Tell them to leave.

55:31.227 --> 55:34.605
‐ We'll go pray for you.
BETSY: Leave, Mom!

55:34.605 --> 55:36.607
Dad, close the door!
JERRY: Okay. Yep.

55:39.735 --> 55:40.987
‐ Is that tender
when I touch it?

55:40.987 --> 55:43.406
BETSY: Yeah.
‐ Yeah. All right.

55:43.406 --> 55:44.824
All right.

55:44.824 --> 55:46.325
You're gonna have
to take some time off.

55:46.325 --> 55:47.827
You can't go down
in the mines like that.

55:47.827 --> 55:49.203
I'll talk
to the management myself.

55:49.203 --> 55:51.080
‐ No, they won't listen to you.

55:52.373 --> 55:53.583
I can't lose my job.

55:53.583 --> 55:55.877
I gotta make enough money
to get out of here.

55:55.877 --> 55:57.336
‐ What are you talking about?

55:59.255 --> 56:02.341
‐ [sighs]

56:02.341 --> 56:04.427
I never told no one
this before.

56:07.763 --> 56:11.142
‐ Bets, I delivered you.

56:12.643 --> 56:14.478
You can tell me anything.

56:17.648 --> 56:19.525
‐ [shakily]
I'm, uh...

56:22.570 --> 56:25.615
I'm, uh...

56:25.615 --> 56:27.575
‐ Bets.

56:27.575 --> 56:28.868
I know.

56:30.036 --> 56:31.829
I know.

56:34.582 --> 56:36.667
‐ And I...

56:36.667 --> 56:40.171
I can't stay here no more.

56:40.171 --> 56:43.174
I gotta be myself.

56:43.174 --> 56:45.051
If I can make enough money
underground,

56:45.051 --> 56:50.014
then I can go live somewhere
where I can just be me.

56:50.014 --> 56:51.182
I love those mines.

56:51.182 --> 56:54.518
I know it sounds strange,
but I do.

56:57.313 --> 56:59.523
I just can't live
like this anymore.

57:03.110 --> 57:07.615
‐ You know...
there's not a day goes by

57:07.615 --> 57:10.952
that I don't think of Shelly

57:10.952 --> 57:12.370
since I lost her.

57:16.415 --> 57:18.334
People shouldn't be allowed
to love somebody

57:18.334 --> 57:19.877
as much as I loved her.

57:22.546 --> 57:27.134
If you gotta go on
and get out of here,

57:27.134 --> 57:29.720
well, then you do that.

57:29.720 --> 57:32.348
I'll even help you,
if you need it.

57:34.809 --> 57:36.852
‐ Okay.
SAMUEL: All right?

57:38.187 --> 57:39.730
‐ I can't take off a month,
though.

57:39.730 --> 57:41.899
Is there anything
you can give me?

57:41.899 --> 57:44.527
A shot to make it heal faster
or something?

57:45.778 --> 57:48.072
‐ There's a new drug

57:48.072 --> 57:50.783
that I've been reading about
in the journals.

57:52.535 --> 57:55.162
They say it's a miracle drug.
I don't know about that.

57:58.416 --> 58:01.419
The FDA and journals
all say it's safe.

58:04.171 --> 58:07.383
Now, I'm gonna give you enough
for a three‐day supply.

58:07.383 --> 58:10.678
You take one now, and then
you take one in the morning.

58:10.678 --> 58:12.304
All right?
BETSY: Okay.

58:12.304 --> 58:13.431
‐ All right.

58:15.057 --> 58:17.435
You only take two a day.

58:17.435 --> 58:19.603
One in the morning,
one at night.

58:19.603 --> 58:21.731
Then come on in
and get an X‐ray.

58:21.731 --> 58:23.149
BETSY: All right.

58:23.149 --> 58:25.276
SAMUEL:
It's gonna be all right.

58:25.276 --> 58:27.611
All right.
I'll talk to your mom and dad.

58:27.611 --> 58:29.113
BETSY: All right.

58:29.113 --> 58:32.116
[dramatic music]

58:32.116 --> 58:35.953
♪ ♪

58:35.953 --> 58:39.415
JERRY: Dear Lord,
please protect our daughter.

58:39.415 --> 58:42.668
I know she's not perfect,
but we love her so much.

58:44.712 --> 58:47.923
But's a hard life
deep under that ground,

58:47.923 --> 58:52.344
and, uh, sometimes we‐‐
we get hurt.

58:52.344 --> 58:54.388
And a lot of us have
to live our entire lives

58:54.388 --> 58:55.723
with that hurt.

58:57.266 --> 58:58.684
Of course,
we're always grateful

58:58.684 --> 59:01.562
for what You've given us
and the...

59:01.562 --> 59:04.440
the mountains
that provide for us.

59:05.483 --> 59:07.777
I beg You, dear Lord,

59:07.777 --> 59:11.030
please take her pain away.

59:11.030 --> 59:14.325
Please save my little girl
from her pain.

59:14.325 --> 59:20.342
HAZEL DICKENS: ♪ Fly away ♪

59:20.342 --> 59:26.048
♪ Little pretty bird ♪

59:26.048 --> 59:28.612
♪ Fly ♪

59:28.612 --> 59:36.160
♪ Fly away ♪

59:36.160 --> 59:41.224
♪ Fly away ♪

59:41.224 --> 59:49.455
♪ Little pretty bird ♪

59:49.455 --> 59:54.229
♪ Where the cold ♪

59:54.229 --> 59:57.422
♪ Winter winds ♪

59:57.422 --> 1:00:02.729
♪ Don't blow ♪

1:00:05.002 --> 1:00:07.129
SAMUEL: These people
carry the burden

1:00:07.129 --> 1:00:10.841
of building this nation
on their backs,

1:00:10.841 --> 1:00:13.886
and they deserve to do it
without pain.

1:00:13.886 --> 1:00:16.847
So if this drug can help,

1:00:16.847 --> 1:00:18.807
well, then
I'm willing to try it.

1:00:18.807 --> 1:00:21.059
[dramatic music]

1:00:21.059 --> 1:00:23.812
RICHARD: We have created

1:00:23.812 --> 1:00:26.356
the greatest painkiller

1:00:26.356 --> 1:00:29.568
in the history
of human civilization.

1:00:29.568 --> 1:00:32.279
‐ This works better than
anything I've ever used before.

1:00:32.279 --> 1:00:34.573
‐ There is something unique
about this drug.

1:00:34.573 --> 1:00:37.201
There's already a spike
in overdoses

1:00:37.201 --> 1:00:38.911
and crime rates.

1:00:38.911 --> 1:00:41.288
RICHARD: They will soon be
the largest profits

1:00:41.288 --> 1:00:42.873
this company has ever seen.

1:00:42.873 --> 1:00:46.251
‐ [laughing]
That is really good.

1:00:46.251 --> 1:00:48.587
‐ How many kids in your school
are on OxyContin?

1:00:48.587 --> 1:00:50.088
‐ I don't know.

1:00:50.088 --> 1:00:52.633
‐ You think maybe that
miracle drug you're selling

1:00:52.633 --> 1:00:55.093
might be a little more
addictive than you said it was?

1:00:55.093 --> 1:00:57.179
‐ We're all
really worried about you.

1:00:57.179 --> 1:00:58.722
‐ It's not the drug
that's the problem.

1:00:58.722 --> 1:01:00.349
It's the addicts
who are abusing it.

1:01:00.349 --> 1:01:02.601
‐ No drug is going to work
perfectly for every patient.

1:01:02.601 --> 1:01:05.062
That's not our job.
Our job is to sell, bitch.

1:01:05.062 --> 1:01:06.814
‐ How dangerous can it be?

1:01:06.814 --> 1:01:08.816
RICK: Everything
we've compiled shows

1:01:08.816 --> 1:01:11.401
that Purdue consistently
oversold the benefits

1:01:11.401 --> 1:01:13.320
and trivialized the risks
of OxyContin.

1:01:13.320 --> 1:01:14.988
JOHN: Those executives
belong in jail.

1:01:14.988 --> 1:01:16.406
RICK: I want Purdue
to feel some pain.

1:01:16.406 --> 1:01:18.033
Let's shake every tree

1:01:18.033 --> 1:01:21.662
and see if we can find
some hard evidence.

1:01:21.662 --> 1:01:22.746
Let's do it!

1:01:22.746 --> 1:01:25.123
‐ People's lives are at stake.

1:01:25.123 --> 1:01:28.836
And a pharma company is lying
about their medicine.

1:01:28.836 --> 1:01:30.921
‐ They will go down.

1:01:30.921 --> 1:01:33.298
‐ Don't worry.
We'll figure this out.

1:01:33.298 --> 1:01:35.217
It's an excellent drug.

1:01:35.217 --> 1:01:39.638
♪ ♪
